Part 1: Configuring My "Base" PuTTY Session
===========================================
Before using MTPuTTY, I set up my primary PuTTY settings (the "mine" profile) to ensure consistent colors and logging.
Open PuTTY and go to the Logging category (under Session).

Enable Logging: I select All session output.
Set Log Path: I click Browse and point it to a folder in my OneDrive so my logs are backed up. (/dir/&H-&D-&M-&T.txt)
Set Conflict Rule: I select Always append to the end of it so I don't overwrite previous logs.
Customize Appearance: I go to Window > Colours to set my foreground/background preferences (e.g., the red text I set up).

Save the Profile: I go back to the Session category.
I Type "mine" in the Saved Sessions box.
I Click Save.

Part 2: Setting up MTPuTTY (Multi-Tabbed PuTTY)
===============================================
MTPuTTY acts as a "wrapper" to manage multiple PuTTY tabs in one window.
Link PuTTY: When I first open MTPuTTY, it asks for the putty.exe location. I click the three dots (...) and navigate to where PuTTY is installed on my VDI. (eg. C:\Program Files\PuTTy\Putty.exe)

Add a New Server:
I click on the Servers menu at the top.
I select Add Server.

Configure Server Properties:
----------------------------
Display Name: I give it a recognizable name (e.g., "AIX_Production" or "Linux_Test").
Server Name: I enter the IP address or Hostname.
PuTTY Session: This is the most important part—I select "mine" from the dropdown. This ensures the colors and OneDrive logging I set up in PuTTY are used here.
Login Credentials (Optional): I can enter my username here if I want MTPuTTY to send it automatically, though leaving the password blank is more secure.
Save: I click OK. My server will now appear in the sidebar on the left.

Part 3: Quick Tips for Daily Use
--------------------------------
I Double-click the server name in the left panel of MTPuTTY to open a new tab.
I Right-click a tab to rename it or duplicate the session.
Default Settings: If I want every new session to have these colors/logs without selecting a profile, I load "mine" in PuTTY, click "Default Settings," and hit Save.
